niz, and Kant and delineates the evolution of twentieth-century phenomenological approaches in the work of Husserl, Merleau-Ponty, Bachelard, and Heidegger. In the book's final section, Casey explores the postmodern theories of Foucault, Derrida, Tschumi, Deleuze and Guattari, and Irigaray.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aPlace (Philosophy). 0aSpace and time. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aaristotle.  abachelard.  aconcept of place.  aconcept of space.  acontemporary thought.  acontinental philosophy.  acreation stories.  adeleuze.  aderrida.  adescartes.  afoucault.  aguattari.  aheidegger.  ahistorical.  ahistory of thought.  ahusserl.  airigaray.  akant.  aleibniz.  amerleau ponty.  amythology.  anewton.  anonfiction study.  aphenomenological approaches.  aphilosophers.  aphilosophical.  aphilosophy theory.  aplato.  areligion.  aspeculations.  atschumi.  awestern philosophy.  awestern thought.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027603140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954564423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954564/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles